03eBut this is exactly the same if you put your mp3 file through Audacity and increase it and play with WMP, or if you put a DirectShow filter that amplifies the volume after your codec output.\\\\nFor example, for a long time, VLC ac3 and mp3 codecs were too low (-6dB) compared to the reference output.\\u003cp\\u003eAt worse, this will reduce the dynamics and saturate a lot, but this is not going to break your hardware.\\u003cp\\u003eVLC does not (and cannot) modify the OUTPUT volume to destroy the speakers. VLC is a Software using the OFFICIAL platforms APIs.\\u003cp\\u003eThe issue here is that Dell sound cards output power (that can be approached by a factor of the quadratic of the amplitude) that Dell speakers cannot handle. Simply said, the sound card outputs at max 10W, and the speakers only can take 6W in, and neither their BIOS or drivers block this.\\u003cp\\u003eAnd as VLC is present on a lot of machines, it\\u0026#x27;s simple to blame VLC. \\u0026quot;Correlation does not mean causation\\u0026quot; is something that seems too complex for cheap Dell support...\\u003cp\\u003eMaybe Dell should advise against playing Metal music and should only allow Céline Dion music, because Metal saturates more...\\u003cp\\u003eEDIT: more details...\\u003cp\\u003ePS: they even provide a BIOS update for the fix... So, of course, VLC was the issue... \\u003ca href=\\\"http://www.dell.com/support/troubleshooting/us/en/04/KCS/KcsArticles/ArticleView?c=us\\u0026amp;l=en\\u0026amp;s=bsd\\u0026amp;docid=557836\\\" rel=\\\"nofollow\\\"\\u003ehttp:\\u0026#x2F;\\u0026#x2F;www.dell.com\\u0026#x2F;support\\u0026#x2F;troubleshooting\\u0026#x2F;us\\u0026#x2F;en\\u0026#x2F;04\\u0026#x2F;KCS\\u0026#x2F;Kcs...\\u003c/a\\u003e\",\"num_comments\":null,\"story_id\":7205759,\"story_title\":\"Installing VLC Media Player voids your speaker warranty\",\"story_url\":\"http://en.community.dell.com/support-forums/laptop/f/3517/t/19492918.aspx\",\"parent_id\":7205759,\"created_at_i\":1391961839,\"r